{
  "name": "Try-Works",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "description": "A design system rooted in Moby-Dick (ch. 96, the try-works). A cold sea is the field; the fire is the load-bearing mark. Ships as web/CSS, Tailwind, Typst slides, an Obsidian theme, a Ghostty terminal preset, and a VS Code code theme. Two modes: Try-Fire (dark) and True Lamp (light).",
  "signature": "Steer by the steady light, not the fire. The cool field (the sea, the whale white, the True Lamp daylight) carries the substance; the fire is the rare mark, kept rare because to fix on it is to lose your bearings (Moby-Dick, ch. 96). The one deliberate exception is the code tier, where a duty to colour-blind readers puts the fire on keywords. See FOUNDATIONS.md.",
  "tiers": {
    "core": "Identity hues used everywhere: ground, sea, fire, whale. These define the brand.",
    "extended": "Working hues added only for code (VS Code, terminal ANSI): a derived green (kelp), red (brick), violet (dusk), plus a blue (tide) and cyan (shoal) drawn from the sea. They never appear on posters, slides, or the web."
  },
